{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Board of Immigration Appeals |nativename = |seal = Seal of the Executive Office for Immigration Review.svg |seal_width = 175px |seal_caption = Seal of the Executive Office for Immigration Review |formed = |jurisdiction = [[Federal government of the United States]] |headquarters = [[Bailey's Crossroads, Virginia]] ([[Falls Church, Virginia|Falls Church]] mailing address) |employees = |budget = |parent_agency = [[Executive Office for Immigration Review]], [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] |chief1_name = David L. Neal |chief1_position = Chairman |chief2_name = Charles Adkins-Blanch |chief2_position = Vice-Chairman |website = [https://www.justice.gov/eoir/board-of-immigration-appeals Board of Immigration Appeals] }}
The '''Board of Immigration Appeals''' ('''BIA''') is an administrative [[appellate court|appellate body]] within the [[Executive Office for Immigration Review]] of the [[United States Department of Justice]].
The BIA reviews the decisions of the [[U.S. immigration court]]s, some decisions of [[U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services]], and immigration violation arrests by [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] and [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]]. BIA decisions are the final administrative action in a given case, and the next stage of appeal after a BIA decision is usually in the [[United States courts of appeals]] if an appeal is allowed by statute.
Most opinions of the BIA are unpublished and do not apply outside of the cases in which they were issued.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.americanbar.org/content/dam/aba/migrated/Board_of_Immigration_Appeals_2.authcheckdam.pdf|title=AMERICAN BAR ASSOCIATION COMMISSION ON IMMIGRATION REPORT TO THE HOUSE OF DELEGATES|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> However, a limited number of BIA decisions are selected for publication in the Administrative Decisions under the Immigration and Nationality Laws of the United States<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.uscis.gov/laws/precedent-decisions|title=Precedent Decisions|work=USCIS|access-date=2018-01-24|language=en}}</ref>. There are currently 28 volumes of administrative precedent decisions under the Immigration and Nationality laws encompassing decisions dating back to 1940.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://myattorneyusa.com/comprehensive-list-of-articles-on-attorney-general-and-bia-precedent-decisions|title=Comprehensive List of Articles on Attorney General and BIA Precedent Decisions {{!}} myattorneyusa|website=myattorneyusa.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref> BIA precedent decisions are legally binding on all components of the Department of Homeland Security ([[United States Department of Homeland Security|DHS]]). A precedent decision may be overruled by a published decision of the Attorney General, by a Federal court, by a subsequent BIA precedent decision, or by a change in the law.
The BIA is located in [[Bailey's Crossroads, Virginia]], and, as of April 2009, had 14 board members, who are administrative judges appointed by the [[U.S. Attorney General]]. The size of the full BIA varies from time to time, depending on resignations, retirements, and new appointments; it may have up to fifteen board members under the current authorizing legislation. Decisions issued by the BIA are by made up of three-member panels in limited circumstances.<ref>{{USCFR|8|1003|1|(e)(6)}}</ref> Otherwise, the vast majority of cases are decided by single panel members.<ref>{{USCFR|8|1003|1|(e)(5)}}</ref> A single panel member can also use a process called summary affirmance, which is used in 10 percent of cases (as of 2008), to affirm the lower court without issuing a written decision.<ref>{{USCFR|8|1003|1|(e)(4)}}; [http://www.justice.gov/eoir/press/06/BIAStreamliningFactSheet030906.htm Fact Sheet: BIA Restructuring and Streamlining Procedures] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108082602/http://www.justice.gov/eoir/press/06/BIAStreamliningFactSheet030906.htm |date=January 8, 2013 }}; [http://www.justice.gov/eoir/press/08/EOIRs22ImprovementsProgressOverview090508v2.pdf Fact Sheet: EOIR’s Improvement Measures –– Progress Overview]</ref>
The BIA is notable in that one need not be an attorney to appear before it representing a client. However, non-attorneys must be part of a BIA-recognized organization (generally a nonprofit), and also have obtained BIA accreditation as individuals. A practice manual<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usdoj.gov/eoir/vll/qapracmanual/apptmtn4.htm|title=Board of Immigration Appeals Practice Manual|date=13 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref> for appearing before the BIA is available from the U.S. Department of Justice. A handbook<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cliniclegal.org/resources/toolkit-bia-recogition-accreditation|title=DOJ Recognition & Accreditation Toolkit - CLINIC|website=www.cliniclegal.org}}</ref> explaining the accreditation and recognition process is available from the nonprofit [[Catholic Legal Immigration Network]] (CLINIC).
