{{Infobox Website | name = Ezmo | favicon = | logo = | screenshot = | caption = | url = http://www.ezmo.com/ | commercial = Yes | type = Free Online Music Player | registration = [[wiktionary:Free|Free]] | owner = [[Fast Search & Transfer]] | language = [[English language|English]], [[German language|German]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] | author = | launch date = 8 June 2007 | current status = Discontinued | revenue = }}
'''Ezmo''' was a free, online music player launched on 8 June 2007 which allowed users to stream and share their personal music collections. Ezmo was in its [[Software release life cycle#Beta|beta]] phase when it was discontinued on 14 March 2008 due to a lack of funding.<ref>[http://ezmo.com/ Announcement from the Ezmo team declaring the project was dead.] {{dead link|date=September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ezmo. CrunchBase Profile|url=http://www.crunchbase.com/company/ezmo|accessdate=2 April 2014|newspaper=[[Techcrunch]]}}</ref> The service used technology from [[Fast Search & Transfer]] <ref>[[Fast Search & Transfer]]</ref> and [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]] Flex. Ezmo was a fully owned subsidiary of [[Fast Search & Transfer]].
== Availability and usage == Ezmo was launched in Europe before it was made available in the United States on 25 October 2007.<ref name="Cnet">{{cite news |last1=Rosoff |first1=Matt |title=Ezmo promises legal music sharing |url=https://www.cnet.com/uk/news/ezmo-promises-legal-music-sharing/ |accessdate=23 September 2018 |publisher=Cnet |date=25 October 2007}}</ref>
Users could upload music from [[iTunes]] or [[Windows Media Player]] to their Ezmo accounts, and share their songs with up to ten friends.<ref name="Cnet" />
A mobile application for Ezmo was launched in early 2008.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}
